Just a couple pointers for next time 👍🏼 1. Yes the masa should be surrounding the filling. You spread the masa far and thin and place the filling in the middle so when you fold it it’ll completely be covered by the
Masa. And 2. Add some chili to the masa mixture. Soak some dried chilies and then blend them with some chicken chicken stock and garlic and put that into the masa so the masa is an orange color and has a bit of spice to it. 👍🏼

snippet.textDisplay:
This is giving me flashbacks to my mom yelling at me when I don't make a good tamale 😂😂😩.
Some tips if you when to remake them:
If you want to make the traditional tamales you want to spread the masa to each side of the leaf (left & right) and it to be thin but not too thin. Because when you fold the tamale it will encase the filling and keep it from leaking out of the tamale while cooking it.
Also the thicker the masa the longer the cooking time will be!
Personally I love tamales de rajas (when there are no rojos) they are simply made with slices of jalapenos and melting cheese, it's sooo yummy.
We also make plain tamales, they are smaller and triangle shaped, we pair them with crema (sour cream) and salsa.

snippet.textDisplay:
Ok I’ve never made a tamal with cheese, so that was a surprise 😳😋
In my costa rican family we make them (the filling) with precooked and seasoned rice, a lot of carrot (alumette cut) and habichuelas (the long green beans), garbanzos, potato (alumette cut), then one dried up plum per tamal and of course pork and chicken, but I myself am vegetarian so we just skip the meat in mine.
And we top them off with lizano sauce which is the same as English sauce.

In costs rica we usually make them in December and it’s tradition for the whole family to do it together because it’s nice, but also you usually need a lot of people because we make 50-60 tamales.
Loved the video :D

snippet.textDisplay: I cringed a bit when he was was forming the tamales.  😬 You’re supposed to spread it almost all the way across, a thin enough layer so you can add fillings to the center and have the masa wraps all the way around, not leaving any filling exposed (except for the top sometimes). You also only fold the bottom. I love seeing people try to new recipes, and I appreciate when cooks attempt classic foreign dishes; even if you don’t get it right, you’re still exposing your audience to something new. 👍🏼❤️👍🏼

you did a really good job julien! thank you for being so respectful to our culture ):
usually there are at least 2 people making/helping with tamales, so you being overwhelmed is t o t a l l y valid!

snippet.textDisplay: Recipe recommendation : (Supposedly vegan according to my mom)   We Replace the lard with vegetable shortening. We also spread the masa out thin with a spoon , it usually covers half the leaf  and reaches all way to bottom and sides. I would at least recommend spreading it out slightly thinner creating a pit and then placing the beans inside so that you are able to fold the masa  on top of the beans, covering them completely. We use chiles en vinagre to make it a little spicy, We slice the jalapeños from it in half and then we put 1 to 2 slices inside with the beans along with vegan cheese.  I would recommend you try the freshly ground masa  from the store  if they have and not masa Harina as they’re not the same And in my opinion produces a better taste. Also not sure that you need to refried beans as you already pointed out they are fried and once you steam the tamales it will be cooked again but up to you. Great job on your first attempt!

snippet.textDisplay:
Julien: says he watched how people made tamales
Also Julien: Throws a huge hunk of masa dead center and doesn't even put filling XD

I've never seen anyone use their hands (LOL) but speaking from experience, tamales aren't easy to make and I think this was a super valiant attempt! I'm not 100% sure how you got those chonkers to cook in an hour because we usually leave them until the house smells like tamales (which can be around 4 hours) but we do make more and use a much larger steamer than yours. If you're into the whole chucking some masa on the hoja you were doing you can try making what my grandmother aptly calls borrachos (basically "drunk" tamales- I'd be careful if googling because I think that means a different type of tamal to different people). Evenly mix your filling into the masa and throw it on the leaf. No need to remember to add your filling or spread it nicely. (you may want to make a little more filling so its a nice ratio) It's something some people do when they're running out of filling just to finish off the masa. You're very gracious when making dishes from other cultures and I'm so here for it!
